---
import Layout from '@layouts/Layout.astro'
import ActionLink from '@components/ActionLink.astro'
import Card from '@components/Card.astro'
import Container from '@components/Container.astro'
import Heading from '@components/Heading.astro'
import Text from '@components/Text.astro'
import ArticleHeader from '@components/Blog/ArticleHeader.astro'
import BlogHero from '@components/Blog/BlogHero.astro'
import PostCard from '@components/Blog/PostCard.astro'
import Prose from '@components/Blog/Prose.astro'
import TableOfContents from '@components/Blog/TableOfContents.astro'

const featuredPost = {
	title: 'Choosing the smallest useful product surface',
	description:
		'Notes from trimming a client dashboard down to the decisions people actually make each morning.',
	href: '/blog/product-surface/',
	publishedAt: '2026-05-18',
	readingTime: '5 min read',
	tags: ['Product', 'UI']
}

const postExamples = [
	{
		title: 'A release note that saved a meeting',
		description:
			'How a plain-language changelog helped support, product, and design make the same call.',
		href: '/blog/release-note/',
		publishedAt: '2026-04-29',
		readingTime: '3 min read',
		tags: ['Writing']
	},
	{
		title: 'When a quieter empty state works better',
		description: 'Replacing a clever illustration with clear next steps in a scheduling flow.',
		href: '/blog/empty-state/',
		publishedAt: '2026-03-12',
		readingTime: '4 min read',
		tags: ['Design']
	}
]

const tableOfContentsItems = [
	{ id: 'context', label: 'Context' },
	{ id: 'decision', label: 'The decision' },
	{ id: 'tradeoffs', label: 'Tradeoffs' },
	{ id: 'shape', label: 'Final shape' }
]
---

<Layout title="Blog Design Lab | Baltazar Andersson">
	<Container
		as="main"
		variant="section"
		class="relative space-y-20 py-24 sm:space-y-24 sm:py-28 lg:space-y-28 lg:py-32"
	>
		<Card
			as="section"
			variant="plain"
			class="rounded-2xl border border-dashed border-border bg-surface-muted/60 p-5 dark:border-indigo-50/15 dark:bg-zinc-950/30 sm:p-7 lg:p-8"
		>
			<ActionLink class="text-sm text-primary transition-colors hover:text-amber-600" href="/">
				Back to portfolio
			</ActionLink>
			<div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-3">
				<Heading as="h1" variant="eyebrow" class="text-left text-foreground dark:text-indigo-50">
					Blog Design Lab
				</Heading>
				<Text class="leading-7 text-foreground dark:text-indigo-100/75">
					Local, unlinked mock for the first blog component batch. This page previews the simple,
					classic direction before the real Markdown-only blog pages adopt it.
				</Text>
			</div>
		</Card>

		<BlogHero
			eyebrow="Writing"
			title="Notes on building useful product interfaces"
			description="Short essays about app development decisions, UI tradeoffs, and the small pieces of writing that keep teams aligned. Markdown first, low ceremony, and grounded in shipped work."
			class="!py-0"
		/>

		<section class="space-y-8 sm:space-y-10" aria-labelledby="post-card-examples">
			<div class="space-y-3">
				<Heading
					as="h2"
					variant="eyebrow"
					id="post-card-examples"
					class="text-left text-foreground dark:text-indigo-50"
				>
					Post Cards
				</Heading>
				<Text class="max-w-2xl leading-7 text-foreground dark:text-indigo-100/75">
					One featured story for the index lead, followed by quieter compact entries for regular
					posts.
				</Text>
			</div>

			<div class="grid gap-6 sm:gap-8 lg:grid-cols-[1.15fr_0.85fr] lg:gap-10">
				<PostCard {...featuredPost} featured />
				<div class="grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-2 sm:gap-8 lg:grid-cols-1">
					{postExamples.map((post) => <PostCard {...post} compact />)}
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="space-y-8 sm:space-y-10" aria-labelledby="article-preview">
			<div class="space-y-3">
				<Heading
					as="h2"
					variant="eyebrow"
					id="article-preview"
					class="text-left text-foreground dark:text-indigo-50"
				>
					Article Preview
				</Heading>
				<Text class="max-w-2xl leading-7 text-foreground dark:text-indigo-100/75">
					A desktop reading layout with side navigation and a mobile-first article flow.
				</Text>
			</div>

			<div class="grid gap-8 sm:gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,1fr)_14rem] lg:items-start lg:gap-12">
				<article
					class="min-w-0 rounded-3xl border border-border bg-surface-elevated/70 p-5 shadow-sm backdrop-blur-md dark:border-indigo-50/10 dark:bg-zinc-950/40 sm:p-8 lg:p-10"
				>
					<ArticleHeader
						eyebrow="Product notes"
						title="Designing the handoff state nobody notices"
						description="A practical look at reducing noise between a scheduling app and the people who operate it daily."
						publishedAt="2026-06-02"
						readingTime="6 min read"
						tags={['App development', 'Product decisions', 'UI tradeoffs']}
					/>

					<Prose>
						<h2 id="context">Context</h2>
						<p>
							The first version of the handoff screen tried to explain every system event. It was
							accurate, but the operators using it only needed to know whether a task was ready,
							blocked, or waiting on someone else.
						</p>
						<p>
							We kept the blog format close to Markdown because the same constraint helps product
							notes: fewer presentation choices, more attention on the decision.
						</p>

						<h2 id="decision">The decision</h2>
						<p>
							The revised screen groups work by status and moves rare details behind a secondary
							link. The main action stays visible, while <code>needs-review</code> remains a useful internal
							state instead of user-facing copy.
						</p>
						<ul>
							<li>Keep the daily view focused on the next operational step.</li>
							<li>Use status labels that match how support talks to customers.</li>
							<li>Move audit details into a quiet, scan-friendly secondary area.</li>
						</ul>
						<blockquote>
							<p>
								A good handoff state should feel obvious enough that nobody remembers learning it.
							</p>
						</blockquote>

						<h2 id="tradeoffs">Tradeoffs</h2>
						<p>
							The simpler view hides some diagnostic detail. That is acceptable because the support
							team reaches for diagnostics after a problem is reported, not while sorting the
							morning queue.
						</p>
						<pre><code>status: ready
primaryAction: "Send confirmation"
secondaryDetail: "View activity log"</code></pre>

						<figure
							class="not-prose my-8 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-border bg-surface-muted dark:border-indigo-50/10 dark:bg-zinc-900/80 sm:my-10"
						>
							<div class="grid min-h-56 place-items-center p-6 text-center sm:p-8 lg:p-10">
								<div>
									<p class="font-heming text-2xl text-foreground dark:text-indigo-50">
										Interface sketch
									</p>
									<p
										class="mt-2 max-w-md text-sm leading-6 text-foreground dark:text-indigo-100/70"
									>
										Local placeholder for a future Markdown image: three status columns, one primary
										action, and muted audit metadata.
									</p>
								</div>
							</div>
							<figcaption
								class="border-t border-border px-5 py-3 text-sm text-muted dark:border-indigo-50/10 dark:text-indigo-100/60"
							>
								A styled placeholder keeps the lab self-contained without external images.
							</figcaption>
						</figure>

						<h2 id="shape">Final shape</h2>
						<p>
							The final direction favors readable defaults and small escape hatches. The table below
							captures the practical split between the visible interface and supporting details.
						</p>
						<table>
							<thead>
								<tr>
									<th>Area</th>
									<th>Visible copy</th>
									<th>Detail level</th>
								</tr>
							</thead>
							<tbody>
								<tr>
									<td>Queue</td>
									<td>Ready to send</td>
									<td>Low</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td>Task detail</td>
									<td>Waiting on approval</td>
									<td>Medium</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td>Activity log</td>
									<td>Reviewed by operations</td>
									<td>High</td>
								</tr>
							</tbody>
						</table>
						<hr />
						<p>
							The result is not flashy. It is a stable writing and reading pattern for explaining
							why a product surface changed and what the team learned from the change.
						</p>
					</Prose>
				</article>

				<aside class="hidden lg:sticky lg:top-28 lg:block" aria-label="Article table of contents">
					<TableOfContents items={tableOfContentsItems} />
				</aside>
			</div>
		</section>
	</Container>
</Layout>
